{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516846"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:47:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:47:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12722"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12722"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.56,0.18,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5177"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59538"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5177"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44946"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1238"},{"type":"tags","id":"1704"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8788"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for routine surveillance of chronic hepatitis B infection. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He does not drink alcohol. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His abdomen is soft and non-tender with no organomegaly. There are no signs of chronic liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImaging studies reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltrasound shows a 1.5 cm hypoechoic lesion in the right lobe of the liver. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT scan confirms arterial enhancement with venous phase washout and capsular enhancement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFibroscan shows no evidence of significant fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory studies show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlpha-fetoprotein 400 \u00b5g/L (\u0026lt;16)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate aminotransferase 35 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine aminotransferase 38 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin 18.6 \u00b5mol/L (2-24).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transarterial chemoembolisation","Hepatic resection","Radiofrequency ablation","Systemic chemotherapy","Liver transplantation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has Barcelona Clinic Liver Cancer (BCLC) stage 0 hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC), diagnosed by typical imaging features in a high-risk patient. The tumour is single, small (\u0026lt;2 cm), and the patient has preserved liver function with no evidence of cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic resection\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment for early-stage HCC in patients with preserved liver function. This patient is an excellent candidate for resection given his normal liver function tests, absence of portal hypertension, and small, single tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransarterial chemoembolisation\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for intermediate-stage (BCLC B) disease with multinodular tumours, or when curative treatments are not possible. It would be inappropriate in this case where curative resection is possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiofrequency ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative to resection, particularly in patients with portal hypertension or other contraindications to surgery. While it can be considered for small tumours, resection remains the gold standard when feasible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is used for advanced (BCLC C) disease with vascular invasion or extrahepatic spread. It has no role in early-stage disease where curative options are available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver transplantation\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for early-stage HCC in patients with significant cirrhosis who are not candidates for resection. This patient has preserved liver function and is suitable for the less invasive option of resection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hepatic resection is the first-line treatment for early-stage hepatocellular carcinoma in patients with preserved liver function.","The diagnosis of hepatocellular carcinoma can be made non-invasively when typical imaging features are present in a high-risk patient.","Barcelona Clinic Liver Cancer (BCLC) stage 0 refers to single tumours less than 2cm with preserved liver function."],"references":["Lubel JS, Roberts SK, Strasser SI, Thompson AJ, Philip J, Goodwin M, et al. Australian recommendations for the management of hepatocellular carcinoma: a consensus statement. Med J Aust. 2021 Jun;214(10):475-483. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33314233/","Wai Ling Khoo TS, Rehman A, Olynyk JK. Tyrosine Kinase Inhibitors in the Treatment of Hepatocellular Carcinoma. In: Tirnitz-Parker JEE, editor. Hepatocellular Carcinoma. Brisbane (AU): Codon Publications; 2019 Oct 24. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549199/figure/Ch7-f0001/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44946"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12722"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44946"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-08T12:31:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-03T18:38:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5177"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59538"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic